(18, 15, 0, 1, '<p>Shebang, welcome, and thank you for all the testing you''ve been doing. It has helped immensely!</p>\n<p>I might as well introduce myself :) I''m the admin around here, and the guy who built this site. I have been doing professional PHP / MySQL development for over 16 years now, and have also worked with a lot of fortune 500 companies during this time too.</p>\n<p>This site really just started out as a hobby, but the featureset has grown so much over the last year that I thought I''d release it and try to make a business out of it. I''m not a fan of advertising-based sites, and so that''s why I''ve implemented a subscription model. The servers need to be paid for, and right now those costs are minimal... but if this site picks up then we will need to start scaling up.</p>\n<p>I really love forums too, and have run and moderated quite a few in the past. I also tried my hand at developing an open source vBulletin clone at one time and have fond memories of the dialup BBS days!</p>\n<p>I want you guys to feel at home here, and to have the tools you need to manage your boards properly. So please feel free to hit me up with any questions or requests you have.</p>\n<p>I have noted the spell check issue and will look into it.</p>\n', 'Shebang, welcome, and thank you for all the testing you''ve been doing. It has helped immensely!\n\nI might as well introduce myself :) I''m the admin around here, and the guy who built this site. I have been doing professional PHP / MySQL development for over 16 years now, and have also worked with a lot of fortune 500 companies during this time too.\n\nThis site really just started out as a hobby, but the featureset has grown so much over the last year that I thought I''d release it and try to make a business out of it. I''m not a fan of advertising-based sites, and so that''s why I''ve implemented a subscription model. The servers need to be paid for, and right now those costs are minimal... but if this site picks up then we will need to start scaling up.\n\nI really love forums too, and have run and moderated quite a few in the past. I also tried my hand at developing an open source vBulletin clone at one time and have fond memories of the dialup BBS days!\n\nI want you guys to feel at home here, and to have the tools you need to manage your boards properly. So please feel free to hit me up with any questions or requests you have.\n\nI have noted the spell check issue and will look into it.', 1466239915, 1269576253, 1466325007, 1269576253, 1, 0, 0, 1, 0),
(19, 15, 18, 6, '<p>I am also not a big fan of ad-based sites but I don''t condemn any site that uses them and if they need my support and the ads are not intrusive I happily disable my adblocking software.</p>\n<p>I like the business model you chose but my personal opinion is that it will take some months (maybe even a full year) before it starts generating money, I hope you can keep the site alive and advertise it enough during that time.</p>\n<p>The sites I have seen fail and die, all of them died due to lack of good advertising and because they failed to keep the relatively small user base interested before other people joined. The post you made on reddit is a good start but don''t let it end there, you''ll have to do that regularly and in different places before you start getting more users and word of mouth advertising takes off.</p>\n<p>Edit: I forgot to mention this, I think it is better to have ads right now, use that money to pay for server costs and disable them once your subscription models starts working than doing the opposite and enabling ads if the subscription model doesn''t work. I say this assuming ads are your backup plan, if they are not then you can just ignore this part.</p>\n', 'I am also not a big fan of ad-based sites but I don''t condemn any site that uses them and if they need my support and the ads are not intrusive I happily disable my adblocking software.\n\nI like the business model you chose but my personal opinion is that it will take some months (maybe even a full year) before it starts generating money, I hope you can keep the site alive and advertise it enough during that time.\n\nThe sites I have seen fail and die, all of them died due to lack of good advertising and because they failed to keep the relatively small user base interested before other people joined. The post you made on reddit is a good start but don''t let it end there, you''ll have to do that regularly and in different places before you start getting more users and word of mouth advertising takes off.\n\nEdit: I forgot to mention this, I think it is better to have ads right now, use that money to pay for server costs and disable them once your subscription models starts working than doing the opposite and enabling ads if the subscription model doesn''t work. I say this assuming ads are your backup plan, if they are not then you can just ignore this part.', 1466240704, 2147483647, 1466240956, 2147483647, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
