(66, 35, 0, 1, '<p>I have added the last login date and current online status to the user profile''s now. I also updated the My Friends page to display the online status too.</p>\n<p>Some things to note though ...</p>\n<p>Status: <span class="uk-text-danger">Online</span>, means the user has viewed a topic within the last 24 minutes. It does not track any other activity, and so if a user logged in and only read some messages or configured their board then the system will not recognize that as being online.</p>\n<p>The Last Login date represents the last time the user manually logged into the site (using the Login / Signup button). If a user is using the "Login automatically on every visit" feature, which uses cookies, then the system will not recognize that as "logging in." So even though it may say a user last logged in weeks ago, they could still be coming to the site regularly using cookies. Having said that, the "automatic" feature does expire every 30 days, and so if the last login date is older than 30 days then that would be an accurate date.</p>\n<p>These things are actually trivial to fix, and I could offer more accurate data (by doing more frequent tracking), but the problem is this has the possibility of introducing a performance impact on the servers. It wouldn''t be noticeable now, but it may be once we scale up to more users.</p>\n<p>So for now, I think this gives you guys a fairly good picture... though I may revisit this once we get more users, and I have some real-world performance data to compare with.</p>\n', 'I have added the last login date and current online status to the user profile''s now. I also updated the My Friends page to display the online status too.\n\nSome things to note though ...\n\nStatus: <span class="uk-text-danger">Online</span>, means the user has viewed a topic within the last 24 minutes. It does not track any other activity, and so if a user logged in and only read some messages or configured their board then the system will not recognize that as being online.\n\nThe Last Login date represents the last time the user manually logged into the site (using the Login / Signup button). If a user is using the "Login automatically on every visit" feature, which uses cookies, then the system will not recognize that as "logging in." So even though it may say a user last logged in weeks ago, they could still be coming to the site regularly using cookies. Having said that, the "automatic" feature does expire every 30 days, and so if the last login date is older than 30 days then that would be an accurate date.\n\nThese things are actually trivial to fix, and I could offer more accurate data (by doing more frequent tracking), but the problem is this has the possibility of introducing a performance impact on the servers. It wouldn''t be noticeable now, but it may be once we scale up to more users.\n\nSo for now, I think this gives you guys a fairly good picture... though I may revisit this once we get more users, and I have some real-world performance data to compare with.', 1467356111, 1269576253, 1467363460, 1269576253, 1, 0, 0, 1, 0),
