(42, 9, 50, 43, 0, 'Alberto Statti - About', '<p>I was born in 1989, Manchester. My mother was in the middle of watching her favourite TV show when she went into labour. She was determined to finish watching but my father had other ideas. He dragged her out of that and hauled her down to the hospital where I was born 30 minutes later (that as a close one).</p>\n<p>We lived in Manchester until I was 7 years old when my parents moved my sister and I to Leeds for my fathers new job. Life in Leeds was quite a bit different, our parents were more hesitant to let us play in the streets and we had an earlier curfew than when we were in Manchester.</p>\n<p>Right after I turned 10 we moved again, but this time, we moved to London which took a little more getting used to than Leeds. London is a very big city compared to Leeds and Manchester (to me at least!)and I was a pretty sheltered kid. I attended a typical London School with a ton of other sheltered kids (Oddly mostly American). I learned about rich city kids and true friendship while I lived there. I also learned a lot about xenophobia. (Some of those American kids really took a beating by random strangers)</p>\n<p>Having to make new friends every couple of years got pretty old so I didnt put much effort into making friends when I moved to London. After about 2 years I changed my mindset and got a few friends. I actually moved to York recently but still speak to all my friends.</p>\n<p>Now that Im an adult, I attended a University and got a degree in IT which I am now hoping to use to bag me a good IT job (I dont care if its at the bottom or as data entry)</p>\n<p>This blog will be used as my diary so to speak where I will keep tabs on everything I do day to day and make monthly updates with the best bits.</p>\n', 'I was born in 1989, Manchester. My mother was in the middle of watching her favourite TV show when she went into labour. She was determined to finish watching but my father had other ideas. He dragged her out of that and hauled her down to the hospital where I was born 30 minutes later (that as a close one).\n\nWe lived in Manchester until I was 7 years old when my parents moved my sister and I to Leeds for my fathers new job. Life in Leeds was quite a bit different, our parents were more hesitant to let us play in the streets and we had an earlier curfew than when we were in Manchester.\n\nRight after I turned 10 we moved again, but this time, we moved to London which took a little more getting used to than Leeds. London is a very big city compared to Leeds and Manchester (to me at least!)and I was a pretty sheltered kid. I attended a typical London School with a ton of other sheltered kids (Oddly mostly American). I learned about rich city kids and true friendship while I lived there. I also learned a lot about xenophobia. (Some of those American kids really took a beating by random strangers)\n\nHaving to make new friends every couple of years got pretty old so I didnt put much effort into making friends when I moved to London. After about 2 years I changed my mindset and got a few friends. I actually moved to York recently but still speak to all my friends.\n\nNow that Im an adult, I attended a University and got a degree in IT which I am now hoping to use to bag me a good IT job (I dont care if its at the bottom or as data entry)\n\nThis blog will be used as my diary so to speak where I will keep tabs on everything I do day to day and make monthly updates with the best bits.', 1468409162, 1443899265, 1468409183, 1443899265, 43, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', 20, 0),
(43, 10, 51, 44, 0, 'About Rates and Rental Surveyors Ltd', '<p>Rates and Rental Surveyors are a team of highly experienced Surveyors, specialising in business rates and rent reductions. We have the expertise and knowledge to identify where savings can be made and have an extremely good track record of successful challenging of appeals.</p>\n<p>We subscribe to a national database and can see your Rating Valuation, appeal history and the assessments of your neighbours, which allows us to have an initial overview of your case. Naturally if you do decide to take matters further then your property will have to be inspected, photographed, measured and you will need to tell us about your lease/rental details as a minimum of case preparation. The Rating Appeal process commences with a proposal made in writing and served on the Valuation Office Agency. You may rest assured that your case will be bolstered and greatly assisted with examples of helpful Tribunal precedents and comparable settlements to negotiate the lowest revised assessment for you.<br />\nSavings! Once the revised Rateable Value or certificate is transmitted by the VOA to the Council, the refund will be processed. We will check your revised business rates statements and make sure you have received the full savings and interest owing to.</p>\n<p>With our extensive experience providing Valuations, Surveys, Lease and Rent Reviews, Business Rate<br />\nAdvice and Dilapidation issues, we are confident that we will provide a professional and personal service to cater for all your property needs.</p>\n<p>Rates and Rental Surveyors Ltd brought in the Ex Chelmsford Valuation Offices Paul Walmsley (BSC,MRICS) to head up its London office which has since grown. Paul is a Chartered Surveyor with over 30 years experience and brings a range of specialist property taxation skills, together with valuation, compulsory purchase and compensation expertise.</p>\n<p>If you would like to find out more the please contact our London office direct on: 0207 193 1767.</p>\n<p>Paul is a full member of the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors Reg. No. 0088800</p>\n<p>Full Corporate membership of the Institute of Revenues Rating and Valuation Reg. No. 018101</p>\n<p>Full Associate membership of the Rating Surveyors Association Reg. No. 708 </p>\n<p>Website - <a href="https://ratesandrentalsurveyorsltd.wordpress.com/">https://ratesandrentalsurveyorsltd.wordpress.com/</a></p>\n', 'Rates and Rental Surveyors are a team of highly experienced Surveyors, specialising in business rates and rent reductions. We have the expertise and knowledge to identify where savings can be made and have an extremely good track record of successful challenging of appeals.\n\nWe subscribe to a national database and can see your Rating Valuation, appeal history and the assessments of your neighbours, which allows us to have an initial overview of your case. Naturally if you do decide to take matters further then your property will have to be inspected, photographed, measured and you will need to tell us about your lease/rental details as a minimum of case preparation. The Rating Appeal process commences with a proposal made in writing and served on the Valuation Office Agency. You may rest assured that your case will be bolstered and greatly assisted with examples of helpful Tribunal precedents and comparable settlements to negotiate the lowest revised assessment for you.\nSavings! Once the revised Rateable Value or certificate is transmitted by the VOA to the Council, the refund will be processed. We will check your revised business rates statements and make sure you have received the full savings and interest owing to.\n\nWith our extensive experience providing Valuations, Surveys, Lease and Rent Reviews, Business Rate\nAdvice and Dilapidation issues, we are confident that we will provide a professional and personal service to cater for all your property needs.\n\nRates and Rental Surveyors Ltd brought in the Ex Chelmsford Valuation Offices Paul Walmsley (BSC,MRICS) to head up its London office which has since grown. Paul is a Chartered Surveyor with over 30 years experience and brings a range of specialist property taxation skills, together with valuation, compulsory purchase and compensation expertise.\n\nIf you would like to find out more the please contact our London office direct on: 0207 193 1767.\n\nPaul is a full member of the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors Reg. No. 0088800\n\nFull Corporate membership of the Institute of Revenues Rating and Valuation Reg. No. 018101\n\nFull Associate membership of the Rating Surveyors Association Reg. No. 708 \n\nWebsite - https://ratesandrentalsurveyorsltd.wordpress.com/', 1468416038, 1443899265, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', 19, 0),
(44, 5, 22, 6, 0, 'Spam, spammers and spam boards', '<p><a href="/home/terms">User agreement</a>:</p>\n<p>&gt;<strong>Don''t spam the GrokBB community</strong></p>\n<p>&gt;You may not post any graphics, text, photographs, images, video, audio or other material that we deem to be junk or spam. Cluttering GrokBB with this sort of content reduces the quality of the GrokBB experience for others.</p>\n<p>What kind of content is considered spam? <a href="/g/Rates_and_Rental_Surveyors_Ltd">This</a> is obvious spam to me, is <a href="/g/Alberto_Statti">an user talking about his blog</a> considered spam?</p>\n<p>What (if anything) is going to be done with spam when it becomes a bigger problem?</p>\n', '[User agreement](/home/terms):\n\n>**Don''t spam the GrokBB community**\n\n>You may not post any graphics, text, photographs, images, video, audio or other material that we deem to be junk or spam. Cluttering GrokBB with this sort of content reduces the quality of the GrokBB experience for others.\n\nWhat kind of content is considered spam? [This](/g/Rates_and_Rental_Surveyors_Ltd) is obvious spam to me, is [an user talking about his blog](/g/Alberto_Statti) considered spam?\n\nWhat (if anything) is going to be done with spam when it becomes a bigger problem?', 1468424588, 2147483647, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', 20, 2),
(45, 2, 1, 1, 0, 'New Feature - Sitewide Chat !', '<p>I have integrated a sitewide chat system! You will see the new feature as a bar at the bottom of every page. On the right is some buttons to chat with users individually or you can join the "GrokBB - General" chat room to have a group conversation with anyone currently on the website.</p>\n<p>It automatically integrates with your existing user account, and it will use the avatar and profile you already have setup in GrokBB. It also allows users who have no account (or are not logged in) to chat too. They will be listed as Guest XXXX. So please be respectful to anyone you see on there and (nudge, nudge, wink, wink) encourage them to sign up :)</p>\n<p>I eventually plan to integrate this into the boards too, so that you can enable a private chat room for your board. The chat system also allows you to create "apps" for it, and so I have other ideas too, like maybe creating some games for it... but we''ll see how it goes. </p>\n', 'I have integrated a sitewide chat system! You will see the new feature as a bar at the bottom of every page. On the right is some buttons to chat with users individually or you can join the "GrokBB - General" chat room to have a group conversation with anyone currently on the website.\n\nIt automatically integrates with your existing user account, and it will use the avatar and profile you already have setup in GrokBB. It also allows users who have no account (or are not logged in) to chat too. They will be listed as Guest XXXX. So please be respectful to anyone you see on there and (nudge, nudge, wink, wink) encourage them to sign up :)\n\nI eventually plan to integrate this into the boards too, so that you can enable a private chat room for your board. The chat system also allows you to create "apps" for it, and so I have other ideas too, like maybe creating some games for it... but we''ll see how it goes. \n\n', 1468519942, 1269576253, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', 25, 1),
(46, 11, 52, 45, 0, 'Building Wren in Windows', '<p>Here are the steps required to build Wren and get it running in Windows.</p>\n<h3>Software Requirements</h3>\n<ul><li><a href="https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=532495&amp;clcid=0x409">Visual Studio 2013</a> </li>\n<li><a href="https://git-scm.com/download/win">Git for Windows</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.python.org/downloads/">Python 2.7</a></li>\n</ul><h3>Wren and its Dependencies</h3>\n<ul><li>Using Git, clone the <a href="https://github.com/munificent/wren">Wren</a> repository on GitHub</li>\n<li>Using Git, clone the <a href="https://github.com/libuv/libuv">Libuv</a> repository on GitHub</li>\n</ul><h3>Building Libuv</h3>\n<ul><li>Open <strong>Git CMD</strong> and cd to the Libuv repository you cloned</li>\n<li>In the root of the repository is a batch file name <strong>vcbuild.bat</strong></li>\n<li>Run the batch file, and it will checkout GYP (a build system), generate the Visual Studio project files, and then automatically build the library for you</li>\n<li>The library will be located in a newly created <strong>Debug\\lib</strong> directory</li>\n<li>If you need to customize the build then you can always open up the Visual Studio Solution named <strong>uv.sln</strong> and build it yourself</li>\n</ul><h3>Building Wren</h3>\n<ul><li>Open Windows Explorer and navigate to the Wren repository you cloned</li>\n<li>Open the Visual Studio Solution located in <strong>util\\msvc2013\\wren.sln</strong></li>\n<li>In the <strong>Solution Explorer</strong>, right-click on the <strong>wren</strong> project and choose <strong>Properties</strong></li>\n<li>Go to <strong>Configuration Properties &gt; C/C++</strong> and double click on the <strong>Additional Include Directories</strong></li>\n<li>Add a <strong>New Line</strong> and choose the location of the Libuv includes directory (i.e. <strong>\\include</strong>)</li>\n<li>Go to <strong>Configuration Properties &gt; Linker</strong> and double click on the <strong>Additional Library Directories</strong></li>\n<li>Add a <strong>New Line</strong> and choose the location of the Libuv lib directory (i.e. <strong>\\Debug\\lib</strong>)</li>\n<li>Go to <strong>Configuration Properties &gt; Linker &gt; Command Line</strong></li>\n<li>Under <strong>Additional Options</strong>, add <strong>/NODEFAULTLIB:LIBCMTD</strong></li>\n<li>Click OK to save all changes and close the Properties window</li>\n<li>In the <strong>Solution Explorer</strong>, expand the <strong>wren</strong> project and right-click <strong>Source Files</strong></li>\n<li>Choose <strong>Add Existing Item</strong> and add the <strong>os.c</strong> file located in the <strong>src\\module</strong> directory</li>\n<li>In the Visual Studio menu bar, go to <strong>Build &gt; Build Solution</strong> (or do it within the <strong>Solution Explorer</strong>)</li>\n<li>You now have a working <strong>Wren CLI</strong> located in <strong>bin\\Debug\\wren.exe</strong></li>\n</ul><h3>Hello Wren!</h3>\n<ul><li><p>Create a file named <strong>hello.wren</strong> and add the following <a href="https://github.com/BrianOtto/GrokBB-Wren/blob/master/examples/hello.wren">code</a></p>\n<p> <code>System.print("Hello Wren!")</code></p>\n</li>\n</ul><ul><li>Place <strong>wren.exe</strong> and <strong>hello.wren</strong> in the same directory</li>\n<li>Open the Command Prompt, cd to that directory and type <strong>wren hello.wren</strong></li>\n<li>Success, you''re a Wren programmer now!!</li>\n</ul>', 'Here are the steps required to build Wren and get it running in Windows.\n\n### Software Requirements\n* [Visual Studio 2013](https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=532495&clcid=0x409) \n* [Git for Windows](https://git-scm.com/download/win)\n* [Python 2.7](https://www.python.org/downloads/)\n\n### Wren and its Dependencies\n* Using Git, clone the [Wren](https://github.com/munificent/wren) repository on GitHub\n* Using Git, clone the [Libuv](https://github.com/libuv/libuv) repository on GitHub\n\n### Building Libuv\n* Open **Git CMD** and cd to the Libuv repository you cloned\n* In the root of the repository is a batch file name **vcbuild.bat**\n* Run the batch file, and it will checkout GYP (a build system), generate the Visual Studio project files, and then automatically build the library for you\n* The library will be located in a newly created **Debug\\lib** directory\n* If you need to customize the build then you can always open up the Visual Studio Solution named **uv.sln** and build it yourself\n\n### Building Wren\n* Open Windows Explorer and navigate to the Wren repository you cloned\n* Open the Visual Studio Solution located in **util\\msvc2013\\wren.sln**\n* In the **Solution Explorer**, right-click on the **wren** project and choose **Properties**\n* Go to **Configuration Properties > C/C++** and double click on the **Additional Include Directories**\n* Add a **New Line** and choose the location of the Libuv includes directory (i.e. **<libuv repository>\\include**)\n* Go to **Configuration Properties > Linker** and double click on the **Additional Library Directories**\n* Add a **New Line** and choose the location of the Libuv lib directory (i.e. **<libuv repository>\\Debug\\lib**)\n* Go to **Configuration Properties > Linker > Command Line**\n* Under **Additional Options**, add **/NODEFAULTLIB:LIBCMTD**\n* Click OK to save all changes and close the Properties window\n* In the **Solution Explorer**, expand the **wren** project and right-click **Source Files**\n* Choose **Add Existing Item** and add the **os.c** file located in the **src\\module** directory\n* In the Visual Studio menu bar, go to **Build > Build Solution** (or do it within the **Solution Explorer**)\n* You now have a working **Wren CLI** located in **bin\\Debug\\wren.exe**\n\n### Hello Wren!\n* Create a file named **hello.wren** and add the following [code](https://github.com/BrianOtto/GrokBB-Wren/blob/master/examples/hello.wren)\n\n   `System.print("Hello Wren!")`\n\n\n* Place **wren.exe** and **hello.wren** in the same directory\n* Open the Command Prompt, cd to that directory and type **wren hello.wren**\n* Success, you''re a Wren programmer now!!', 1468649621, 1269576253, 1468803034, 1269576253, 45, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', 31, 0),
